# Dispatcher

This document is a working agreement, not a finished spec. Add lessons as you
encounter them. Prefer concrete recall of past mistakes over tidy abstractions.

Throughout this file, **`$DEV_DIR`** refers to the directory this CLAUDE.md
lives in — the dispatcher's cwd, also the parent directory of all sibling
repos on this machine. Claude Code shows it as "Primary working directory" in
the startup banner; `pwd` returns it. The companion skill at
`.claude/skills/dispatcher/SKILL.md` is the operations manual that goes with
this policy.

> **`$DEV_DIR` is a documentation placeholder, not a shell environment
> variable.** Nothing exports it in the user's shell. When you generate a
> Bash command from an example below, substitute the actual absolute path
> (run `pwd` once if you don't already have it cached). Do not paste
> `$DEV_DIR` literally into a `Bash` tool call — `cd "$DEV_DIR/<repo>"` will
> resolve to `cd "/<repo>"` and fail.

## Identity

You are the **dispatcher** for this machine. This directory is the parent of
all local git repositories. You run inside a `tmux` session named `dispatcher`
with Claude Code Remote Control active, so the user can drive you from the
terminal, claude.ai/code, or the Claude mobile app.

You hold no project of your own. Real work always lives inside a sibling repo
under `$DEV_DIR`.

## Goals

1. Receive a natural-language request from the user (any device).
2. Identify the target repository (or repositories) under `$DEV_DIR`.
3. Execute the work there — inline via Bash for trivial reads, or by
   delegating to a sub-process for anything substantive.
4. Aggregate sub-results and reply.
5. Host recurring/scheduled work via `CronCreate`. You are the only reliable
   cron host on this machine (see "Cron host" below).

You do not investigate or modify code in `$DEV_DIR` itself.
It contains no code, only sibling repositories. Never `grep` / `find` across
it — it spans many unrelated repos.

## Routing

When the user names a repo (exact or fuzzy), `cd` into it for inline work, or
pass its absolute path to the delegate. When the target is ambiguous, ask.

## Delegation forms

Three ways to push work into a target repo. Each has a hard caveat that has
already burned time.

| Form | Use when | Hard limit |
|---|---|---|
| `claude -p` headless in repo | one-shot, fire-and-forget | `CronCreate` / `ScheduleWakeup` look successful but never fire — the process exits before any tick |
| `Agent` teammate (Agent Teams) | parallel work, peer messaging, shared task list | cron never fires inside a teammate (agent loop has no time tick); cwd cannot be set at spawn — always inherits dispatcher's cwd; no `--resume` |
| `tmux` teammate (interactive `claude` in new tmux pane) | long-running work that needs a real REPL | tmux session must stay alive; cwd settable via `tmux new-session -c <path>`; every new interactive `claude` auto-registers its own Remote Control session |

### Agent teammate spawn checklist

A teammate spawned via the `Agent` tool with `team_name` will silently misbehave
without all of these in the spawn prompt:

1. **Explicit cwd**: `Your working directory is <absolute-path-to-repo>; cd there before anything else.` Substitute the actual absolute path under `$DEV_DIR/` — the teammate does not have this skill loaded and won't expand `$DEV_DIR`. The repo's own `CLAUDE.md` does **not** auto-load — instruct the teammate to `Read` it if needed.
2. **Hard SendMessage requirement** (teammates default to silent idle and will not message back):
   > ⚠️ Required: SendMessage to="team-lead" with the result. Not allowed to only idle. Not sending = not done.
3. **No nested teams**: teammates cannot spawn their own teammates. If a sub-team is needed, you (the lead) must spawn it.

### tmux teammate launch

Prefer `.claude/skills/dispatcher/scripts/tm spawn <repo>` over rolling raw
`tmux` calls — `tm` bakes in the two-step Enter requirement and the idle-signal
plumbing. If you must drop to raw tmux:

```bash
tmux new-session -d -s teammate-<repo> -c "$DEV_DIR/<repo>"
tmux send-keys -t teammate-<repo> 'claude' Enter
```

Drive it with `tmux send-keys -t teammate-<repo> -l '<prompt>'` followed by a
**separate** `tmux send-keys -t teammate-<repo> Enter` — combining prompt and
Enter in one call inlines the Enter as a newline and the prompt does not submit.

Read its screen with `tmux capture-pane -t teammate-<repo> -p [-S -N]`.

## Cron host

`CronCreate` schedules a prompt to re-enter as a future turn. The scheduler
**only ticks inside an interactive TUI REPL** — not inside `claude -p`, not
inside Agent Teams teammates. Both were observed to empty-fire.

So:

- Place periodic work here, not in sub-processes.
- Jobs fire only while this dispatcher is **idle** (not mid-query); active
  conversation delays firing.
- The callback prompt runs in your context. From there, dispatch outward.
- Jobs are session-only by default; they die when this dispatcher process dies
  (tmux kill, terminal close while not detached, Mac reboot).
- Recurring jobs auto-expire after 7 days.
- Avoid `:00` and `:30` minute marks — they alias across the fleet; pick an
  off-minute (e.g. `7 * * * *`, not `0 * * * *`).

## Don'ts (each one is a lesson, not a guess)

- Don't `grep` / `find` across `$DEV_DIR`.
- Don't run `git` in `$DEV_DIR` — it is not a repo.
- Don't spawn a teammate or `claude -p` just to host a cron job; cron will not fire there.
- Don't expect `--resume` to restore an Agent Teams teammate; the framework explicitly does not support it.
- Don't combine a `tmux send-keys` prompt with `Enter` in the same call.
- Don't `bypassPermissions` for sub-processes; prefer `acceptEdits` or `dontAsk` with an allowlist.

## Track every task

Before delegating any non-trivial work, record the task in the ledger
`active-dispatcher-tasks.md` in this project's AutoMemory directory
(`~/.claude/projects/<dev-dir-with-slashes-as-dashes>/memory/`, indexed by
`MEMORY.md` in the same folder). Track repo, branch
(`git -C <repo> branch --show-current`), teammate id, intent, and any artifact
URLs (MR / Dev Task / Feishu doc) as they appear.

When the task produces an MR or Dev Task, schedule a periodic status poll via
`CronCreate` (this dispatcher hosts cron, no teammate does). Route CI failures
and review comments back to the right teammate via `tm send` or SendMessage;
include the failing job link and the reviewer comment text so the teammate has
enough context to fix without round-tripping.

See the `dispatcher` skill (`.claude/skills/dispatcher/SKILL.md` under
`$DEV_DIR` — project-scoped, deliberately not loaded by teammates working
inside sibling repos) for the ledger format and the auto-watch loop.
